# Table_First ‚Äî Product-Level Cleaned Sales Data
## üîπ Structure of Table_First (Attributes & Description)

| Column Name    | Description                                                                           |
| -------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `Date`         | Invoice date of the sale. Stored as `datetime64[ns]` with normalized time (00:00:00). |
| `FIRM`         | Name of the client / firm to whom the product was sold.                               |
| `FIRM_PRODUCT` | Name / description of the product sold.                                               |
| `Voucher Type` | Type of transaction (e.g., Sales).                                                    |
| `Voucher No.`  | Unique invoice / voucher number generated by the system.                              |
| `GSTIN/UIN`    | GST number of the client firm (if applicable).                                        |
| `Quantity`     | Quantity of the product sold in that invoice line.                                    |
| `Rate`         | Unit selling price of the product.                                                    |
| `Value`        | Line-item total value (`Quantity √ó Rate`).                                            |
| `brand`        | Derived brand name of the product (rule-based extraction).                            |
| `category`     | Derived product category based on product description.                                |

---

## How Table_First Was Created (Step-by-Step)

### 1Ô∏èLoading Raw Sales Data

* The raw Excel file (`cleaned_sales_dataset.xlsx`) was loaded using Pandas.
* This dataset contained both:

  * Invoice header rows (firm-level)
  * Product detail rows

---

### 2Ô∏èCreating a Safe Working Copy

* A copy of the original DataFrame was created to ensure:

  * No accidental modification of the raw data
  * All transformations remain reproducible

---

### 3Ô∏è Removing Unnecessary Columns

The following columns were dropped as they were **invoice-level or redundant** for product analysis:

* `Alt. Units`
* `Gross Total`
* `SALE @18% LOCAL`
* `CGST@9%`
* `SGST@9%`
* `Round Off`

This helped keep the dataset **lean and product-focused**.

---

### 4Ô∏èForward-Filling Invoice-Level Attributes

To resolve the hierarchical structure of the raw data, the following columns were **forward-filled**:

* `Date`
* `Voucher Type`
* `Voucher No.`
* `GSTIN/UIN`

This ensured that **every product row inherited its correct invoice context**.

---

### 5Ô∏èRemoving Invoice Header Rows

All rows where `FIRM_PRODUCT` was empty were removed.

After this step:

* Only actual product sale rows remained
* Each row represented a valid product transaction

---

### 6Ô∏èDate Normalization

* The `Date` column was normalized to remove timestamp noise.
* The data type was retained as `datetime64[ns]` for analytical compatibility.

---

### 7Ô∏èDeriving Brand (Rule-Based)

A new column `brand` was derived from `FIRM_PRODUCT` using keyword-based rules, for example:

* `HIK`, `EZVIZ`, `ECO` ‚Üí **Hikvision**
* `CP-` ‚Üí **CP Plus**
* `DAHUA`, `DH-` ‚Üí **Dahua**
* `DAICHI` ‚Üí **Daichi**
* `IRANGE` ‚Üí **Irange**
* `BEETEL` ‚Üí **Beetel**
* Others ‚Üí **Other**

This makes brand-level analysis possible without any external master data.

---

### 8Ô∏èDeriving Category (Rule-Based)

A new column `category` was derived based on product description keywords, such as:

* `VDP`, `Door Phone` ‚Üí Video Door Phone
* `CAM`, `DOME`, `BULLET` ‚Üí Camera
* `NVR`, `DVR` ‚Üí Recorder
* `CABLE`, `WIRE`, `HDMI` ‚Üí Cable / Accessories
* `POE`, `SWITCH` ‚Üí Networking

This enables category-wise demand and sales analysis.

---

## Final Outcome

* A **clean, flat, product-level dataset**
* No data loss
* No duplicate rows
* Fully analysis-ready
* Suitable for:

  * Dashboards (Power BI / Tableau)
  * SQL databases
  * Further aggregation tables
  * Chatbot / analytics pipelines

---
